\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 Disordered eating is both a high prevalence and high impact disease. In spite of the success of the development of continuous eating detection systems, the eating characteristics that differentiate normal from healthy eaters remain unknown. By quantifying various eating related characteristics, we uncover a more comprehensive profile of the complex behavior that leads to disordered eating. To this end, we performed a free-living experiment in which we integrated data from both a smart watch and NeckSense sensor suite to identify various eating-related characteristics. Specifically, we integrated these data to quantify eating speed, identify social vs. solitary eating behavior by voice recognition, and categorize posture while eating (standing, sitting). We also investigated whether the detect body-focused repetitive behaviors such as nail biting, which is a common comorbidity with eating disorders and mental health. By moving beyond simple eating detection into quantifying various eating related characteristics, we provide a more comprehensive profile of the complex behavior that leads to disordered eating.
