\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 Obesity is a global epidemic of enormous consequence, affecting over 500 million people worldwide and predisposing them for cancer, heart disease and diabetes. In addition, the global outlook continues to worsen, with the global age-standardized bmi growing 2.1 kg m-2 from 1985 to 2017 (rural). The growing importance of this problem has motivated researchers and clinicians to innovate new treatments that could help reverse this trend. Continuous eating detection systems (CDS), in particular, have garnered attention as they promise to provide a bonanza of behavioral data that could drive novel data-driven, personalized treatment. Further, CDSs could provide the foundation for novel real-time interventions, which are a class of treatments that have proven to be effective.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 CDSs are user-worn sensors that utilize user produced data to detect eating behavior. So far, researchers have found a variety of approaches, including motion based, camera based, and ear can detect eating with moderate to high accuracy. However, many of these devices have not been tested or are less effective in naturalistic experiments. In addition, many are either cumbersome, or carry a social stigma that limits widespread use. Lastly, most of these devices aim purely to detect eating events, and stop short of providing the context that characterizes these eating events. This contextual information, such as the quantity of food consumed, the speed at which it is consumed, or whether eating is social or solitary, have all been linked to obesity, and thus would be crucial in developing personalized interventions. Thus, it is critical that we develop a wearable that is effective outside of a lab, discrete or social acceptable to wear, and collects information on eating context in addition to eating events.
